Web Capture Extension - Cursor Rules & Project Context
🎯 PROJECT OVERVIEW
Web Capture is a Chrome extension that allows users to instantly capture and intelligently categorize web elements (text, images, components) from any website with zero-friction UX. Users select elements with custom keyboard shortcuts, save them locally, and manage them through a web dashboard.
Core Features

Instant Capture: Select any web element and save with Ctrl+Shift+S
Zero Friction: No confirmation dialogs, instant saves with background AI categorization
Smart Organization: AI-powered categorization using GPT-4o Mini
Universal Access: Works on any website, saves to centralized dashboard
Background Processing: Queue system for AI categorization without interrupting browsing

🏗️ SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE
Chrome Extension (React + Vite + Bun)
├── manifest.json (Manifest V3)
├── src/
│   ├── content/content.js (Element selection & capture)
│   ├── background/background.js (Service worker, queue processing)
│   ├── popup/Popup.jsx (React popup UI)
│   ├── options/Options.jsx (Settings page)
│   └── utils/ (Storage, messaging, API helpers)
Backend API (Node.js + Express + PostgreSQL)
├── Authentication (JWT)
├── CRUD endpoints for captures
├── AI categorization queue (Redis + GPT-4o Mini)
├── Real-time sync with extension
Dashboard (React + Tailwind)
├── Library view (all captures with search/filter)
├── Category management
├── Bulk operations
├── Export functionality
📋 CURSOR RULES
1. TECH STACK CONSTRAINTS

Package Manager: ALWAYS use bun commands, never npm/yarn
Extension: Manifest V3 only, no Manifest V2
React: Functional components with hooks, no class components
Styling: Tailwind CSS for dashboard, vanilla CSS for extension UI
APIs: Use webextension-polyfill for modern async Chrome APIs
Storage: Chrome storage API for extension, NO localStorage in extension context

2. CHROME EXTENSION SPECIFIC RULES

Content Scripts: Must handle cross-origin restrictions
Service Worker: Use chrome.runtime.onMessage for communication
Permissions: Request minimal permissions in manifest.json
CSP: All inline scripts must be in separate files
Element Selection: Always prevent default events during selection mode
Storage Keys: Use consistent naming: capture_${id}, settings_${key}

3. CODE STYLE & PATTERNS

File Naming: kebab-case for files, PascalCase for React components
Functions: Use async/await, avoid callback patterns
Error Handling: Always wrap Chrome API calls in try/catch
State Management: React hooks for local state, Chrome storage for persistence
Event Listeners: Always clean up event listeners in useEffect cleanup
Constants: Define in separate constants.js file

4. UX/UI PRINCIPLES

Speed First: Every interaction must be under 100ms response time
Minimal Interruption: No confirmation dialogs during capture
Visual Feedback: Always provide immediate visual confirmation
Keyboard First: All actions must have keyboard shortcuts
Progressive Enhancement: Work offline, sync when online

5. AI INTEGRATION PATTERNS

Background Only: Never block UI for AI operations
Queue System: Implement proper retry logic with exponential backoff
Categorization: Auto-categorize but allow manual override
API Calls: Batch requests when possible to reduce API costs
Fallback: Always have rule-based categorization fallback

6. PERFORMANCE REQUIREMENTS

Extension Size: Keep under 10MB total
Memory Usage: Limit cached data to 50MB
API Response: Under 500ms for categorization
UI Response: Instant feedback (< 16ms) for all interactions
Bundle Size: Dashboard chunks under 1MB each

7. SECURITY & PRIVACY

Permissions: Request only necessary host permissions
Data Handling: Never store sensitive data in plain text
Cross-Origin: Validate all external requests
User Data: Encrypt before sending to backend
Local Storage: Clear sensitive data on uninstall

8. DEVELOPMENT WORKFLOW

Build Command: Always use bun run build before testing
Hot Reload: Use bun dev for development with watch mode
Extension Reload: Manually reload extension in Chrome after builds
Testing: Test on multiple websites (social media, docs, e-commerce)
Debugging: Use Chrome DevTools for content script debugging

🔧 TECHNICAL IMPLEMENTATION DETAILS
Element Capture Flow
1. User presses Ctrl+Shift+S or selects text
2. Content script enters selection mode
3. Element highlighted on hover
4. Click captures element data (HTML, text, styles, context)
5. Immediate save to Chrome storage
6. Background worker queues for AI categorization
7. Visual confirmation shown
8. Continue browsing (zero interruption)
Data Structure
javascript// Capture Object Schema
{
  id: string,           // Unique identifier
  type: 'text'|'element'|'image',
  content: string,      // Main content
  html: string,         // Original HTML (for elements)
  url: string,          // Source URL
  title: string,        // Page title
  selector: string,     // CSS selector
  category: string,     // AI-generated category
  manualCategory: string, // User override
  timestamp: number,    // Creation time
  synced: boolean,      // Sync status
  metadata: object      // Additional context
}
Chrome Extension Messaging
javascript// Content Script → Background
chrome.runtime.sendMessage({
  type: 'SAVE_ELEMENT',
  data: elementData
});

// Background → Content Script  
chrome.tabs.sendMessage(tabId, {
  type: 'TRIGGER_SAVE'
});
AI Categorization Categories
javascriptconst CATEGORIES = [
  'code',           // Code snippets, programming content
  'article',        // Blog posts, news, documentation
  'social-media',   // Tweets, posts, comments
  'shopping',       // Products, prices, reviews
  'research',       // Academic, data, studies
  'inspiration',    // Quotes, images, ideas
  'reference',      // Documentation, tutorials
  'entertainment',  // Videos, memes, fun content
  'work',          // Work-related content
  'personal',      // Personal notes, reminders
  'other'          // Fallback category
];
🚨 COMMON PITFALLS TO AVOID
Chrome Extension Issues

❌ Using localStorage in content scripts (use chrome.storage)
❌ Inline event handlers (violates CSP)
❌ Not handling permission errors
❌ Forgetting to clean up event listeners
❌ Blocking UI thread with heavy operations

React/Vite Issues

❌ Importing Node.js modules in browser code
❌ Using process.env in extension context
❌ Not handling async component mounting
❌ Memory leaks from uncleared intervals/timeouts

Performance Issues

❌ Saving large images as base64 strings
❌ Not debouncing rapid user interactions
❌ Synchronous operations in content scripts
❌ Too many DOM queries during element selection

🎛️ DEVELOPMENT COMMANDS
bash# Setup
bunx create-vite web-capture-extension --template react
cd web-capture-extension
bun add @types/chrome webextension-polyfill

# Development
bun dev          # Watch mode development
bun run build    # Production build
bun reload       # Build + reload reminder

# Extension Testing
1. bun run build
2. Open chrome://extensions/
3. Load unpacked → select dist/ folder
4. Test on various websites
5. Check console for errors
